{"key":"processedPost-9501731","value":{"id":9501731,"first":9501406,"last":14887768,"when":1230401891,"utime":"12/27/08 08:18 PM","cleanedPost":"Don't listen to the brf tek bashers.&nbsp; I grew mushrooms for over 20 years before that tek even came out in the 90's.&nbsp; For some reason, new and intermediate growers seem to think it's like riding a bike with training wheels for babies, but that's far from the truth.&nbsp; No other method will deliver the biological efficiency of the brf tek, nor will any other method take you from spores to fruits quicker, IF done properly.<br />Perhaps you're not mixing the water and verm first before adding the brown rice flour?&nbsp; Normally, you'd intuitively think to mix all the dry ingredients first before adding water, but with the brf tek, you want to mix the water and verm first, and then slowly stir in the flour.&nbsp; Failure to do so can lead to compacting.<br />Finer verm holds more water than course verm.&nbsp; A good rule of thumb if you're already following all the steps properly, is to make your substrate next time a bit drier than the recipe calls for.&nbsp; A slightly dry substrate will colonize faster, and then you can easily dunk/soak for 24 hours to put the moisture it needs for flushing later on, after full colonization.<br />RR"}}